The WASP-26 Exoplanetary System


Overview

WASP-26 is a star with 0.86 times the mass of the Sun, and 1.22 times its radius. It is located 824.39 light years away from the solar system and is estimated to be 6 billion years old, as compared to the Sun which is roughly 4.6 billion years old.

WASP-26 is known to have 1 exoplanets in orbit around it.


Exoplanets in the WASP-26 system


WASP-26 b

WASP-26 b was discovered by the SuperWASP observatory, in 2010-09, using the transit method. Its semi-major axis is 0.04 astronomical units, as compared to Earth's which is 1 astronomical unit. The mass of WASP-26 b is 270.300 times the mass of Earth. The radius of WASP-26 b is 13.563 that of Earth. At more than 50 Earth masses, WASP-26 b is a gas giant, a planet whose mass is mostly made up of hydrogen and helium, like Jupiter and Saturn in our solar system.
description: 3D visualisation and gravity simulation of the exoplanet system WASP-26, which contains 1 exoplanets and was discovered by the SuperWASP.
